This is the best emulator. And I know you've heard everyone say this about every emulator, so let me at least tell you why, so you can see if you value what I value. Hands down, the graphics are super crisp. The other feature I like is the ability to save and load state very quickly. Just double click one side of the screen for save, the other for load. Brilliant! And the rewind button -- forget about it! I use it all the time when I get butter fingers and fall off a cliff.   Now, the one thing that annoys me is the default place the developer put the fast forward button. It's on the R2 Button of my SNES30 8bitdo controller. I keep accidentally fast forwarding. No problem. I try to delete fast forwarding from that button. No idea how. No problem. So I disable fast forwarding -- it still happens when you press the R2 Button. I just remapped it to the select button since I only play one player. Just super annoying. Please work on that. Don't force feed us that fast forward.   Other than that, I love this emulator. I uninstalled my old emulator and will refuse to buy a SNES emulator until I see a Nostalgia branded SNES emulator.

I have to say, just due to the dynamic d-pad, this emulator has the best touch based controls on the market. It feels so much better than having to look over for some fake buttons to make sure you're pressing what you need to press. However, I think you guys should consider adding an option for the dynamic d-pad that allows it move along with your finger when you swipe outside it's area. Sometimes I swipe a little ways past the d-pad, and when I swipe in the opposite direction to turn, I'm so far away from the d-pad, I can't turn around; with a NES game, it can really hurt your playthrough. It'd also be nice if you guys added an option for the dynamic d-pad that disables diagonal presses, as some games consider it a deadzone, which, once again, is the difference between life and death in an NES game.

replyContent: As we already discussed via email, this is intended behavior. The PAL version of the NES runs at 50 FPS, whereas the NTSC version runs at 60 FPS. So it is perfectly fine that the speed of a game changes when you switch the video mode.
